    <h1><acronym title="Scalable Vector Graphic">SVG</acronym> Debian CD Cover</h1>

    <iframe src="params.html"></iframe>

    <p>A while back I made a <a href="raster.html">CD cover</a> for debian 2.2rc1. It was one of my first artsy sort of things and I was happy with it. I even shared it with the debian people and got put in the <a href="http://www.debian.org/CD/artwork/">FAQ</a>. Unfortunately I was too busy to keep updating the text as releases came out and eventually it was booted.</p>

    <p>I made a replacement in <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/SVG11/">SVG</a> which adds the labels using <a href="http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/standards/Ecma-262.htm">ecmascript</a> and the <a href="http://www.w3.org/DOM/">DOM</a>. If your browser can view them, you can generate one using <a href="params.html">this form</a>. (The form also allows you to view the URL needed for viewers like <a href="http://xml.apache.org/batik/">Batik</a> which can take a URL, but can't do a HTML form.) If necessary, you can also <a href="images/svg_cover_files.tgz">download the files</a> and use Batik locally. (Questions marks are allowed in file names on some OS's though and so <code>file:</code> urls do not necessarily work with arguments.) The how of how it was done follows.</p>

    <hr/>

    <p>I was wandering back through old stuff and noticed those covers and thought, <q>hmm&hellip;, it is just some image compositing with some blending&hellip; I bet I could to that in svg and let people make the text whatever they want.</q> So, this page is me figuring out how to do that&hellip;</p>

    <p>I need this image to fade at the border and to do that I will need to mask with a radial gradient. Such a svg would look <a href="image/gradient/svg">something like this</a>:</p>

    <a href="image/gradient/svg">
      <img src="image/gradient/svg" type="image/svg+xml" alt="Test Gradient"/>
    </a>

    <p><a href=".../lib/svg/web start/?svg=.../lib/debian/cover/image/gradient/svg">View in Batik.</a></p>

    <p>I used <a href="http://www.almackey.com">Al Mackey</a>'s <a href=".../image/by/Al Mackey/linux/fox/png">Linux fox</a> (which I can no longer find a working link for). I thought it would work better in a vector format so I took a bit and <a href=".../image/mascot/linux/fox">vectorized</a> it.</p>

    <a href=".../image/mascot/linux/fox">
      <img src=".../image/mascot/linux/fox" type="image/svg+xml" alt="Linux Fox"/>
    </a>

    <p><a href="../svg_web_start/?svg=../covers/images/linuxfox.svg">View in Batik.</a></p>

    <p>The <a href=".../image/logo/Debian/swirl">swirl</a> is just a converted version of the <a href="http://www.uk.debian.org/logos/#open-use">open use logos</a>.</p>

    <a href=".../image/logo/Debian/swirl">
      <img src=".../image/logo/Debian/swirl" type="image/svg+xml" alt="Debian Swirl"/>
    </a>

    <p><a href="../svg_web_start/?svg=../covers/images/swirl.svg">View in Batik.</a></p>

    <p>Likewise the <a href=".../image/logo/Debian">lettering</a> is just broken out from an <a href="http://www.uk.debian.org/logos/#open-use">open use logo</a>.</p>

    <a href=".../image/logo/Debian">
      <img src=".../image/logo/Debian" type="image/svg+xml" alt="Debian Logo"/>
    </a>

    <p><a href="../svg_web_start/?svg=../covers/images/debian.svg">View in Batik.</a></p>

    <p>The process now is just compositing and adding some labels. SVG makes importing and manipulating images pretty easy. There is a basic <a href="image/cover/template/svg">template</a> which uses ecmascript to insert labels.</p>

    <a href="image/cover/template/svg">
      <img src="image/cover/template/svg" type="image/svg+xml" alt="Debian Logo"/>
    </a>

    <p><a href="../svg_web_start/?svg=image/cover/template/">View in Batik.</a></p>

    <p>The parameters can be specified using <a href="params.html">a form</a> or can be inserted in the URL manually. All of the work is done by a script in the image and there is no server generated content.</p>

    <p>The parameters used by the program are:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>release: the name of the release (ex. "2.2 revision 3" or "woody 3.0 rc2")</li>
      <li>discname: the name of the disc (ex. "binary disc 1")</li>
      <li>discid: a short id for the disc (ex. "1")</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Here is an <a href="image/cover/template/svg?discname=test%20disc%20name&amp;release=woody%201.2%20rc2&amp;discid=1">example</a> of the image with the query string ?discname=test%20disc%20name&amp;release=woody%201.2%20rc2&amp;discid=1</p>

    <a href="image/cover/template/svg?discname=test%20disc%20name&amp;release=woody%201.2%20rc2&amp;discid=1">
      <img src="image/cover/template/svg?discname=test%20disc%20name&amp;release=woody%201.2%20rc2&amp;discid=1" type="image/svg+xml" alt="Sample Disk Image"/>
    </a>

    <p><a href="../svg_web_start/?svg=image/cover/template/svg?discname=test%20disc%20name&amp;release=woody%201.2%20rc2&amp;discid=1">View in Batik.</a></p>

    <p>The filters are in an external file and the <a href="http://www.adobe.com/svg/">Adobe viewer</a> doesn't deal well with that. Your best bet is <a href="http://xml.apache.org/batik/">Batik</a> which supports the external filters correctly.</p>

